silent about the subject. This volume’s focus on conversion offers a novel approach to the dislocations of the postsocialist experience. In eight well researched ethnographic accounts the authors analyze a range of missionary encounters as well as aspects of conversion and "anti-conversion" in different parts of the region, thus challenging the problematic idea that religious life after socialism involved a simple "revival" of repressed religious traditions. Instead, they unravel the unexpected twists and turns of religious dynamics, and the processes that have challenged popular ideas about religion and culture. The contributions show how conversion is rooted in the disruptive qualities of the new "capitalist experience" and document its unsettling effects on the individual and social level.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aChristianityzRussia (Federation). 0aConversion. 0aMissionszRussia (Federation). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aBroz, Ludek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngelhardt, Jeffers, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLankauskas, Gediminas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeel, J.D.Y., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPelkmans, Mathijs, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPelkmans, Mathijs, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVallikivi, Laur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVaté, Virginie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWanner, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBo